-- 
Crude Oil Volatility Falls as Futures Edge Lower for Second Day

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-03-25T21:38:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-25/crude-oil-volatility-falls-as-futures-edge-lower-for-second-day.html
Oil options volatility fell as the
underlying futures slipped less than 0.2 percent for the second
consecutive day.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
May, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 30.9 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 32.3 percent yesterday and 37.6 percent a week ago.  Crude for May delivery fell 20 cents to settle at $105.40 a
barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Prices have risen
3.5 percent since March 18, the first weekly advance in three.
They have gained 31 percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
May $100 puts with 1,211 lots changing hands. They fell 11 cents
to $1.01 a barrel. May $110 calls, the next most active
contract, lost 28 cents to $1.41 a barrel with 1,133 contracts
trading. One contract is for 1,000 barrels of oil.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  June $130 calls were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 4,049 lots changing hands. They lost 9 cents to
67 cents a barrel. The next most active option, May $100 puts,
were unchanged from the day before at $1.12 on 3,382 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
39,138 contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 38,916 and
June $150 calls with 38,883.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 